{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600520/1930120801/0179.xml":{"full_text":"A-16\nTRAVEL DECREASES\nTO VIRGINIA SHRINES\nl&tate Chamber Says Traffic\nDropped 20 Per Cent in\nEastern Part.\nBy the Associated Press.\nRICHMOND, Va., December B.\u2014Sta\ntistics compiled by the Virginia State\nChamber of Commerce for the first 10\nmonths es this year showed that tour\n\u201c~ist traffic in Eastern Virginia decreased\n20 per cent and declined by 7Mj per\ncent in the Valley, in comparison with\nthe figures for the corresponding period\nof 1929. The figures were based on the\nrecords of historic shrines.\nGeneral business depression was given\nas the principal cause for decrease in\nthe number of tourists. The statistics\nahowed there was no decrease until\nearly in July. Preceding tlmt time many\nof the shrines In all of Vir\nginia showed slight increases.\nUrge Placing of Markers.\nIt was pointed out' that instructive\nmarkers placed in and near Alexandria\nchecked the decrease in vfcitors at his\ntoric shrines, and in October the num\nber of tourists showed slight increases.\nThis fact led the State Chamber to\nrecommend to the local Chambers of\nCommerce in Richmond and Fred\nericksburg that steps be taken to post\nadequate markers directing visitors to\nthe shrines of those cities.\nIn this connection it w r as pointed out\nthat, in comparison with all other\nshrines in the State, fewer persons visit\nthose in Richmond than any other. The\nfigures for the 10 months this year\nshowed that the number of visitors at\nall Richmond shrines during the entire\nperiod did not equal the daily average\nfer the Summer months at Mount Ver\nhon.\nThe statistics showed that in July of\n\u2666his year 62,000 persons visited Mount\nVernon, last year in the same month\nthere were 69,000: In August, 1930, the\nnumber was 70.000; in 1929 It was\nfif.ooo: with 45.000 visitors in Septem\nber there was 1 a decrease of 10,000 in\ncomparison with the figures for Sep\ntember, 1929. and with 32,000 visitors\nIn October*the figure was 3,000 less\nthan the figure for the same month\nlast year.\nVisitors at Monticello.\nAt Monticello the number of visitors\nIn January. February, March and May\nallowed a slight increase, but with 60,-\n000 in June the figure this year was\n32,000 less than that for June, 1929.\nTne number in July was 71,000. In\nJuly of last year there were 83,000 visi\nters, in August the number dropped\nfrom 11,000 to 8,000 and in September\nIt dropped from 8,000 to 6,000. The\nOctober figure this year was 5,000, 1,000\nless than the same month last year.\n_ Jamestown Island likewise showed\nslight Increase in the number of tour\nists during the late Winter and early\nSpring months, but July saw the 4,800\ntourists recorded last year drop to 4,300.\nPREACHING MISSION\nIN OLD CHARON CHAPEL\nHistoric Episcopal Church to Be\nScene of Special Services\nfor Week.\nBbeclal Dispatch to The Star.\nCAMERON, Va., December 8. A\npreaching mission was opened vester\noay at Old Sharon Episcopal Chapel,\non the Telegraph road, in Fairfax\nCounty. It will continue through next\nSunday morning, with services each\nnight except Saturday. It is being con\nducted by Capt. Frank Bloxham of\nthe Church Army, formerly of England\nand now a student at the Theological\nSeminary, who conducted similar mis\nsions last year in several of the mis\nsion churches of Fairfax County. Spe\ncial music is provided by James Roe,\nwho is also a student at the seminary.\nThe Mission Church, this year in\ncharge of James Valliant. a senior at\nthe seminary, assisted by William Latte\nand Eugene Hallam. was the first mis\nsion to be established by students of\nthe Theological Seminary. Its first\nchapel was erected in 1848. During the\nCivil War the, building was destroyed\nby fire. The present building is the\nthird to be buUt on this site and was\nerected 30 years ago.\nAmong' the prominent Episcopalians\nWho have served this chapel while stu\ndents at the seminary are Phillips Brooks,\nBishop of Massachusetts and noted di\nvine of the last century; Dr. Berryman\nGreen, present dean of the seminary;\nDr. W. Cosby Bell of the present fac\nulty; Dr. W. R. Bowie, rector of Grace\nChurch. New York City; Bishop W. P.\nRemington of the missionary district\nof Eastern Oregon and the present\nBishop Tucker of Virginia.\nWhen G. Urquhart Watts was\n\u2022sked to resign as organist, the entire\nchoir of Elgin High Church, at Elgin,\nScotland, struck in a bodv. and at last\nreports were still out while 20 volun\nteers filled their places.\nReal Estate Loans\n(D. C. Property Only)\n6%\n|No Commission Charged j 1\nVou can take 12 years to B\nI pay off your loans without the n\nexpense of renewing. SI,OOO 0\nfor $lO per month, including\ninterest and principal. Larger 1\nor smaller loans at proportion\nate rates.\nPerpetual\nBuilding\nAssociation\nI Established 1881\nLargest in Washington J\nAssets Over $23,000,000\nI Cor. 11th and E N.W.\nJAMES BERRV President\nip EDW ARD C BAl.fr Z. Secretary j\nSays: This Health\nDrink Makes Old\nFolks Feel Younger\nSpry-Walk\u2014Vigorous Activity\u2014\ni Weeks\u2019 Trial Costa\nAlmost Nothing\nAB over.the world million* are\ntalking about these rejuvenating\nI magic minerals that fill elderly peo\nj pie with the Joy of living.\nJust try it for 4 weeks\u2014and see j\nif you don\u2019t feel better and more i\nenergetic than you have for years.\nAll you have to do is to take one\nhalf a teaspoon of Kruse hen Salts\nIn a glass of hot water before break\nfast every morning\u2014don\u2019t miss a\nmorning.\nIt\u2019s astonishing how quickly it\nbrings natural activity to liver, bow- j\nels, kidneys and glands.\nAn 85 cent bottle lasts 4 weeks\nand you can get it at Peoples Drug\nI Stores or any drug store in the\nworld Feel gloriously alive once\nmore.\u2014Advertisement.\nBargain Annex Opens at 8 A.M. Tuesday for This E?^95555555555555555555555555555955559\nHecht Co. Bargain Annex\n4\